"Aumann H.H., Ruzmaikin A., Teixeira J.","Frequency of severe storms and global warming",2008,"Geophysical Research Letters","35","19", L19805,"","",,,10.1029/2008GL034562,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-57749199285&partnerID=40&md5=75e2f5fb00696911d216babcb855fbfa","Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, 4800 Oak Grove Drive, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States","Aumann, H.H., Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, 4800 Oak Grove Drive, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States; Ruzmaikin, A., Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, 4800 Oak Grove Drive, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States; Teixeira, J., Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, 4800 Oak Grove Drive, Pasadena, CA 91109, United States","We use five years of data from the Atmospheric Infrared Sounder (AIRS) to develop a correlation between the frequency of Deep Convective Clouds (DCC) and the zonal mean tropical surface temperature. AIRS data show that the frequency of DCC in the tropical oceans is very temperature sensitive, increasing 45% per 1 K increase of the zonal mean surface temperature. The combination of the sensitivity of the DCC frequency to temperature indicates that the frequency of DCC, and as a consequence the frequency of severe storms, increases at the rate of 6%/decade with the current +0.13 K/decade rate of global warming. This result is only qualitatively consistent with state-of-the-art climate models, where the frequency of the most intense rain events increases with global warming. Copyright 2008 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric radiation; Clouds; Global warming; Infrared devices; Infrared instruments; Microwave antennas; Military operations; Ocean currents; Sounding apparatus; Storms; Surface properties; AIRS datums; Climate models; Rain events; Severe storms; Surface temperatures; Temperature sensitives; Tropical oceans; Zonal means; Atmospheric temperature; climate modeling; frequency analysis; global warming; severe weather; storm",,,,,,"Aumann, H.H., Broberg, S., Elliott, D., Gaiser, S., Gregorich, D., Three years of Atmospheric Infrared Sounder radiometric calibration validation using sea surface temperatures (2006) J. Geophys. Res, 111, pp. D16S90. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006822; Aumann, H.H., Gregorich, D., AIRS observations of deep convective clouds (2006) Proc. SPIE, 6301, pp. 63010J. , doi: 10.1117/ 12.681201; Aumann, H.H., Gregorich, D.T., Broberg, S.E., Elliott, D.A., Seasonal correlations of SST, water vapor, and convective activity in tropical oceans: A new hyperspectral data set for climate model testing (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett, 34, pp. L15813. , doi:10.1029/2006GL029191; Chahine, M.T., The Atmospheric Infrared Sounder (AIRS): Improving weather forecasting and providing new data on greenhouse gases (2006) Bull. Am. Meteorol. Soc, 87, pp. 911-926; Emanuel, K.A., The dependence of hurricane intensity on climate (1987) Nature, 326, pp. 483-485; Goody, R.M., (1995) Principles of Atmospheric Physics and Chemistry, , 324 pp, Oxford Univ. Press, New York; Hartmann, D.L., (1994) Global Physical Climatology, Int. Geophys, 56. , 411 pp, Academic, San Diego, Calif; Held, I.M., Soden, B.J., Robust responses of the hydrological cycle to global warming (2006) J. Clim, 19, pp. 5686-5699; Knutson, T.R., Tuleya, R.E., Impact of CO 2-induced warming on simulated hurricane intensity and precipitation: Sensitivity to the choice of climate model and convective parameterization (2004) J. Clim, 17, pp. 3477-3495; Randel, W.J., Wu, F., Vömel, H., Nedoluha, G.E., Forster, P., Decreases in stratospheric water vapor after 2001: Links to changes in the tropical tropopause and the Brewer-Dobson circulation (2006) J. Geophys. Res, 111, pp. D12312. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006744; Reynolds, D.W., Observations of damaging hailstorms from geosynchronous satellite digital data (1980) Mon. Weather Rev, 108, pp. 337-348; Rosenlof, K.H., Stratospheri